data.title: The 100 Best Movies With End in the Title
data.meta_description: Over 50 filmgoers have voted on the 100 Best Movies With End in the Title. Current Top 3: Dead End, End of Days, Seeking a Friend for the End of the World ...
data.text:
Ranked By

428 votes

53 voters

How many movies with end in the title can you name? This list ranks the best movies with end in the name, whether they're documentaries, dramas, horror movies, or any other genre of film. Do you have a favorite movie with end in the title? Categorizing movies by words in their titles is kind of uncommon, but that's a big part of why this list is so fun to scroll through. There's probably one movie with end in the title you think of right away, but you might be shocked to see how many others exist as well.

Notable films with end in the title include Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End, This Is the End, and John Dies at the End, although there are many more examples on this list. This poll is interactive, meaning you can vote the end movies up or down depending on how much you like them.

Latest additions: It Ends with Us

Over 50 Ranker voters have come together to rank this list of The 100 Best Movies With End in the Title

Sylvia Sidney, Humphrey Bogart, Joel McCrea

A gripping, gritty crime drama, this early American film exposes the raw underbelly of the hardscrabble slums where it's set while showcasing the incredible talents of a young Humphrey Bogart as a vicious gangster. The movie masterfully intertwines the themes of futility, corruption, and despair, leaving viewers with a lingering sense of dread. It's no wonder that it remains a highly influential corner-stone of the film noir genre.

Released : 1937

Directed by : William Wyler

Also ranks # 10 on The Best 1930s Gangster Movies

Also ranks # 6 on The 130+ Best Movies of 1937

Arnold Schwarzenegger, Gabriel Byrne, Kevin Pollak

A pulse-pounding supernatural thriller, this film stars Arnold Schwarzenegger as a world-weary ex-cop who must prevent the apocalypse by protecting a woman chosen to bear Satan's child. With its high-stakes plot, intense action sequences, and ominous atmosphere, it keeps viewers on the edge of their seats. Though rooted in religious themes, it transcends genre boundaries to deliver an exhilarating and nail-biting cinematic experience.

Released : 1999

Directed by : Peter Hyams

In this poignant and bittersweet dramedy, Steve Carell and Keira Knightley embark on an emotionally charged road trip as Earth faces inevitable doom from an approaching asteroid. As they navigate a crumbling society and confront their own regrets, deep-seated fears, and unexpected feelings, it is ultimately a story about human connection and the power of acceptance. This unique blend of existential anxiety and offbeat humor makes for an unforgettable cinematic experience.

Released : 2012

Directed by : Lorene Scafaria

Jake Gyllenhaal, Michael Peña, Natalie Martinez

This riveting, visceral cop drama unfolds through the lens of handheld cameras, giving it an intimate and gritty sense of realism. Centered on the intense bond between two LAPD officers, portrayed with raw authenticity by Jake Gyllenhaal and Michael Peña, it's a relentless and emotional exploration of friendship, loyalty, and sacrifice in the line of duty. The powerful performances and innovative storytelling techniques make this a standout entry in the police thriller genre.

Released : 2012

Directed by : David Ayer

Also ranks # 361 on The Best Movies Roger Ebert Gave Four Stars

Simon Pegg, Nick Frost, Paddy Considine

A clever and wonderfully inventive British sci-fi comedy, this film wraps up the beloved Cornetto Trilogy directed by Edgar Wright and starring Simon Pegg and Nick Frost. A group of friends reunites to complete a long-abandoned pub crawl, only to discover an alien invasion that threatens the fate of humanity. With its rapid-fire wit and satirical social commentary, this perfect blend of humor, action, and heart is bound to keep audiences entertained until the very last pint.

Released : 2013

Directed by : Edgar Wright
